    "excerpt": "Art is unique to humans. Images created by generative AI are imitations and cannot be recognized as works of art. In February of this year, the United States Copyright Office (USCO) suddenly revoked aut...",
    "body_en": "<p style=\"text-align: justify; \">Art is unique to humans. Images created by generative AI are imitations and cannot be recognized as works of art. In February of this year, the United States Copyright Office (USCO) suddenly revoked author Chris Casitano's webtoon copyright. It has been only six months since the author sparked heated discussion as a case of being granted copyright for a webtoon drawn through mid-journey, which generates an appropriate image when a word or sentence is entered. In the world of pure art, this result is consistent with the position that AI works are plagiarism because they are a collection and imitation of existing works.</p> <p> <br/> </p> <p>Let?셲 take a closer look. First, the reversal of the Copyright Office's decision was due to the fact that the author did not have complete control over Midjourney. In other words, it is true that the writer's writing was created as an image, but it does not embody the image in the writer's head, and it is difficult for even the writer of the writing to accurately predict what image will be created. The author was precisely ?쁝ssisted??by AI. And we decided to call this result ?쁟ollaboration??</p> <p> <br/> </p> <p>Second, art is a history of imitation. Dreaming of becoming the future Leonardo da Vinci, the homework that came up after enrolling in art school for the first time as a child was ?쁟roquis.?셒hen I opened the book with the title ?쁂roquis 1?? on one side there were not pictures of people, but someone had already drawn them in pencil, such as a running girl and an adult man squatting down. I had to draw the pencil drawings on the blank side as closely as possible, down to the thickness of the lines.</p> <p>It was no different at piano academy. He played Hanon, Bach, and Schubert over and over again until he got tired of it, and at a competition, he memorized the pieces and played them, winning a prize. The Schubert we all know was influenced by Beethoven, and modern painters refer to Monet or Van Gogh, as well as images from Adobe Stock and Pinterest.</p> <p> <br/> </p> <p>Interesting works were exhibited at Tapgol Art Museum. Artist Noh Jin-ah brought her mother to the center of the art museum. My mother said to people passing by, ?쏻hat I want is for me to live the rest of my life doing what I want to do like I do now.?쒿his work is a robot designed to analyze the facial expressions of visitors using deep learning technology and then imitate them or make facial expressions appropriate to the situation. This work was evaluated as reminding the audience of their own mother and arousing empathy.</p> <p>In 2013, the robot Nao danced on stage with a dance troupe, and last year, the Kim Ok-ryun Ballet gave the robot a role. We can be moved even by works of art that were not produced by humans.</p> <div class=\"cheditor-caption-wrapper\" style=\"text-align: center;\"> <figure class=\"cheditor-caption\" style=\"border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); background-color: #d97706; margin: 0px; display: inline-block; width: 660px;\"> <img alt=\"20230325054202_iomlepun.jpg\" src=\"https://www.artinsight.co.kr/data/tmp/2303/20230325223554_vlxdcqan.jpg\" style=\"width: 660px; height: 199px;\"/> <figcaption class=\"cheditor-caption-text\" style=\"margin: 6px 10px 6px 10px; text-align: left; line-height: 18px; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: -0.04em; text-align:justify;\">Noh Jin-ah, there is no time to spare (Seoul Art Guide)</figcaption> </figure> </div> <p>Before Lee Sedol's match against AlphaGo, humans had already lost in a chess match between Deep Blue (IBM) and Garry Kasparov in 1997. However, in 2005, in a match between three teams consisting of a team of chess experts, a supercomputer, and an amateur and a computer, the amateur team won.</p> <p>In a later TED lecture, Kasparov advised people to face their fear of machines and grow, saying that they can complement each other by working as a team with computers. Also, I didn't forget these words.?쏧f you create a successful machine, it is also the victory of the human who designed the machine. (As always, machine?셲 triumph was a human triumph.)??/p> <p> <br/> </p> <p>?쁌oravec?셲 Paradox??by American robotics engineer Hans Moravec is also in the same context.?쏷hings that are easy for robots are difficult for humans. Things that are easy for humans are also difficult for robots. (Hard problems are easy and easy problems are hard.)??Most current technologies are specialized in one field. So more people are showing fear (covered as rejection).</p> <p>However, many companies are developing future technology businesses as solution businesses. The view is that technology can create an environment that can make people's lives more enriched.</p> <div class=\"cheditor-caption-wrapper\" style=\"text-align: center;\"> <figure class=\"cheditor-caption\" style=\"border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); background-color: #d97706; margin: 0px; display: inline-block; width: 660px;\"> <img alt=\"4.jpg\" src=\"https://www.artinsight.co.kr/data/tmp/2303/20230325054418_saddrvyr.jpg\" style=\"width: 660px; height: 359px;\"/> <figcaption class=\"cheditor-caption-text\" style=\"margin: 6px 10px 6px 10px; text-align: left; line-height: 18px; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: -0.04em; text-align:justify;\">Deep blue vs. Garry Kasparov</figcaption> </figure> </div> <p> <br/> </p> <p>Going back to art, the word ?쁀I??is becoming more familiar, but the proposition that art was the last responsibility of humans is breaking down. In particular, it is not a matter of victory or defeat, but rights such as copyright, emotions, and livelihood are all complex, so the more sensitive discussion has been put on hold and has come to this point. Baduk and chess have already acknowledged the victory of machines in terms of ?쁲kill??and ?쁬emorization??and have long since moved forward with collaboration that combines human ?쁦ntuition??and ?쁳echnology?? Art can also take a leap forward based on recent events.</p> <p> <br/> </p> <p>A work of art can be seen as consisting of the artist, the work, and the interpretation. In other words, the audience also occupies one axis with equal weight. As someone who enjoys culture, wouldn't you like to open the door to a new world you've never seen before? Don?셳 you want to see with your own eyes the triumph of artists born with extremely ordinary talents? Humans will always try. If you can give an even greater impression, feel free to use technology!</p> <div class=\"cheditor-caption-wrapper\" style=\"text-align: center;\"> <figure class=\"cheditor-caption\" style=\"border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); background-color: #d97706; margin: 0px; display: inline-block; width: 660px;\"> <img alt=\"Picture1.jpg\" src=\"https://www.artinsight.co.kr/data/tmp/2303/20230325053738_ztrzzkgk.jpg\" style=\"width: 660px; height: 660px;\"/> <figcaption class=\"cheditor-caption-text\" style=\"margin: 6px 10px 6px 10px; text-align: left; line-height: 18px; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: -0.04em; text-align:justify;\">* This illustration was created with Stable Diffusion, a generative AI.</figcaption> </figure> </div> ",
